00:04:23.933 --> 00:04:26.880
"When Tabitha Thatch argued,
her little sister Julie

00:04:26.880 --> 00:04:29.640
always thought about cats.

00:04:29.640 --> 00:04:31.682
It was rare that Tabitha
argued, much more common

00:04:31.682 --> 00:04:33.140
that she agreed to
rules or demands

00:04:33.140 --> 00:04:35.240
her mother or the
world imposed on her,

00:04:35.240 --> 00:04:37.490
and then did the opposite
of what she'd agreed to.

00:04:37.490 --> 00:04:39.940
But when she did argue,
her jaw relaxed open

00:04:39.940 --> 00:04:42.210
and her voice,
high-pitched and ragged,

00:04:42.210 --> 00:04:45.500
folded in on itself
in 100 tissue paper

00:04:45.500 --> 00:04:48.580
layers of connotation,
implication, meaning,

00:04:48.580 --> 00:04:52.300
all of her yowling 'protest' in
a way that you couldn't ignore.

00:04:52.300 --> 00:04:56.441
You could listen to Tabitha
arguing like a cat for hours.

00:04:56.441 --> 00:04:58.440
Julie-- her own voice
like a dog's, she thought,

00:04:58.440 --> 00:05:02.836
short and hoarse and barky-- had
listened to Tabitha for hours.

00:05:02.836 --> 00:05:04.210
You could listen
and you would be

00:05:04.210 --> 00:05:06.520
struck by how raw and
vibrant that voice was.

00:05:06.520 --> 00:05:08.817
But then you would realize
that Tabitha was just

00:05:08.817 --> 00:05:10.400
saying she was going
to go to the mall

00:05:10.400 --> 00:05:12.110
and buy Adderall to
swallow with beer

00:05:12.110 --> 00:05:14.651
and then hang around the food
court talking about the Misfits

00:05:14.651 --> 00:05:15.570
with some college kid.

00:05:15.570 --> 00:05:18.970
In a raw and vibrant and catlike
way she would tell you that.

00:05:18.970 --> 00:05:21.500
And you would believe in her.

00:05:21.500 --> 00:05:22.930
Linda, Tabitha and
Julie's mother,

00:05:22.930 --> 00:05:24.930
had never been vulnerable
to Tabitha's voice.

00:05:24.930 --> 00:05:28.686
And Julie had always hated
Linda a little bit for that.

00:05:28.686 --> 00:05:30.310
They were fighting
now, Tabs and Linda.

00:05:30.310 --> 00:05:32.800
Their voices came through
the walls of Julie's bedroom

00:05:32.800 --> 00:05:35.621
like foreign talk
radio on the AM dial.

00:05:35.621 --> 00:05:37.120
Julie sat up on the
edge of her bed,

00:05:37.120 --> 00:05:39.290
recently stripped of its
alphabet-patterned case

00:05:39.290 --> 00:05:41.870
and replaced with a more
grown-up deep green color

00:05:41.870 --> 00:05:44.140
that reminded her
of rainforests.

00:05:44.140 --> 00:05:46.810
She felt her long hair sticking
up in crazy roller-coaster

00:05:46.810 --> 00:05:48.960
loops at the back of her head.

00:05:48.960 --> 00:05:52.304
The air of the room
was somehow just wrong.

00:05:52.304 --> 00:05:54.720
Like Lucy in 'Voyage of the
Dawn Treader,' she had slipped

00:05:54.720 --> 00:05:57.220
into another dimension, one in
which she was not able to get

00:05:57.220 --> 00:05:59.497
any sleep before her
algebra test the next day,

00:05:59.497 --> 00:06:01.830
one in which the red digital
clock was blinking midnight

00:06:01.830 --> 00:06:05.800
at her in some sick parody
of 'good morning.' She went

00:06:05.800 --> 00:06:08.890
into the hallway, still in her
white Apple Records T-shirt

00:06:08.890 --> 00:06:11.450
and boxers, sat on the floor
outside Linda's bedroom,

00:06:11.450 --> 00:06:15.229
curled her legs up to her
body, and listened to them.

00:06:15.229 --> 00:06:17.520
Everything has to have a
reeeason, that's your problem,

00:06:17.520 --> 00:06:18.580
Tabitha was saying.

00:06:18.580 --> 00:06:19.810
What if my reason
is that I just want

00:06:19.810 --> 00:06:21.790
to spend all day lying
in a field or something?

00:06:21.790 --> 00:06:23.540
And writing long letters
to ex-boyfriends?

00:06:23.540 --> 00:06:25.190
What if that's my reason?

00:06:25.190 --> 00:06:28.560
I don't give a shit what
your reason is, Linda said.

00:06:28.560 --> 00:06:30.180
I don't care how
boring or irrelevant

00:06:30.180 --> 00:06:31.740
you think your
classes are, either.

00:06:31.740 --> 00:06:33.890
You think I don't spend
eight or nine hours a day

00:06:33.890 --> 00:06:36.350
doing boring and
irrelevant stuff?

00:06:36.350 --> 00:06:37.770
I think you're
spending right now

00:06:37.770 --> 00:06:40.150
doing boring and irrelevant
stuff, said Tabitha.

00:06:40.150 --> 00:06:44.120
Does right now count toward
those eight or nine hours?

00:06:44.120 --> 00:06:46.470
It's called
survival, said Linda.

00:06:46.470 --> 00:06:48.650
You do what you have
to in order to survive.

00:06:48.650 --> 00:06:50.620
It's not called
fun or quit school

00:06:50.620 --> 00:06:53.910
so I could go out with boys and
work at a fucking video arcade

00:06:53.910 --> 00:06:55.900
and smoke pot in
the house all day.

00:06:55.900 --> 00:06:58.250
At least smoke
pot in the garage.

00:06:58.250 --> 00:07:01.430
I'm an adult, said Tabitha.

00:07:01.430 --> 00:07:04.000
I can possibly make decisions
without subjecting them

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:05.760
to some neurotic
process of analysis

00:07:05.760 --> 00:07:07.730
about what might
possibly go wrong or--

00:07:07.730 --> 00:07:09.060
You're 17, said Linda.

00:07:09.060 --> 00:07:13.500
And the video arcade is a good
job, said Tabitha, mother.

00:07:13.500 --> 00:07:15.010
Linda laughed.

00:07:15.010 --> 00:07:18.750
Julie buried her cheeks deeper
into her bare bony knees.

00:07:18.750 --> 00:07:21.230
There are no good
jobs, Linda said.

00:07:21.230 --> 00:07:23.580
There are only lucrative
jobs that you hate.

00:07:23.580 --> 00:07:26.270
Your job is neither
lucrative, nor do you hate it.

00:07:26.270 --> 00:07:28.952
I'll move out, said Tabitha.

00:07:28.952 --> 00:07:29.660
That got a laugh.

00:07:29.660 --> 00:07:30.160
That's cool.

00:07:30.160 --> 00:07:31.682
I like this place.

00:07:31.682 --> 00:07:32.890
"I'll move out, said Tabitha.

00:07:32.890 --> 00:07:34.932
I'll move out, and maybe
Julie will come with me.

00:07:34.932 --> 00:07:36.973
And you won't have us
hanging around all the time

00:07:36.973 --> 00:07:38.287
making your life miserable.

00:07:38.287 --> 00:07:39.370
You're stoned, said Linda.

00:07:39.370 --> 00:07:41.536
I'm not going to argue with
you while you're stoned.

00:07:41.536 --> 00:07:44.330
Ewwww, you're
stoooooned, said Tabitha.

00:07:44.330 --> 00:07:45.910
Get out of my room, said Linda.

00:07:45.910 --> 00:07:46.420
go to bed.

00:07:46.420 --> 00:07:47.860
And you're going back to
school in the morning.

00:07:47.860 --> 00:07:49.100
You're going to tell them
you changed your mind

00:07:49.100 --> 00:07:49.683
about leaving.

00:07:49.683 --> 00:07:52.690
Ewwww, get out of my
rooooom, said Tabitha.

00:07:52.690 --> 00:07:56.870
The TV came on immediately,
some infomercial.

00:07:56.870 --> 00:07:58.910
There was a snort
and then a stomp.

00:07:58.910 --> 00:08:01.792
And then Julie's eyes were
blinded by the lamplight.

00:08:01.792 --> 00:08:04.000
Tabitha stormed into the
hallway and slammed the door

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:05.220
behind her.

00:08:05.220 --> 00:08:08.810
She turned and her eyes fell to
the ball of Julie at her feet.

00:08:08.810 --> 00:08:10.520
She stopped before her sister.

00:08:10.520 --> 00:08:12.770
What the fuck are you doing
in the hallway? she asked.

00:08:12.770 --> 00:08:14.470
Were you spying on us?

00:08:14.470 --> 00:08:17.240
Yes, Julie said.

00:08:17.240 --> 00:08:18.960
Tabitha stared down at her.

00:08:18.960 --> 00:08:20.457
Julie stared back up.

00:08:20.457 --> 00:08:22.790
When Tabitha got like this,
you could not be reasonable.

00:08:22.790 --> 00:08:26.650
You only had to match
her, crazy for crazy.

00:08:26.650 --> 00:08:29.280
Even in the dark hallway,
Julie thought her older sister

00:08:29.280 --> 00:08:32.169
was very beautiful-- her
hair, hay-blonde like Julie's,

00:08:32.169 --> 00:08:34.630
bleached and highlighted
in pink like celery stalks

00:08:34.630 --> 00:08:36.380
in red water.

00:08:36.380 --> 00:08:38.701
Her skirt torn, her
stockings striped,

00:08:38.701 --> 00:08:40.909
her shirt full of rhinestones
like the constellations

00:08:40.909 --> 00:08:43.032
that Julie liked to
memorize from books

00:08:43.032 --> 00:08:45.240
and try to see through the
fluorescent haze of Austin

00:08:45.240 --> 00:08:46.860
streetlights.

00:08:46.860 --> 00:08:49.819
The rhinestones
spelled out NO FUTURE.

00:08:49.819 --> 00:08:52.110
Tabitha put her hands on her
hips and pursed her mouth.

00:08:52.110 --> 00:08:55.384
Her lips were painted in
red and outlined in black.

00:08:55.384 --> 00:08:56.800
The epaulets of
her leather jacket

00:08:56.800 --> 00:08:59.544
rose and fell as she breathed.

00:08:59.544 --> 00:09:00.460
Come on, Tabitha said.

00:09:00.460 --> 00:09:01.849
Let's get out of here.

00:09:01.849 --> 00:09:02.640
Where are we going?

00:09:02.640 --> 00:09:03.940
Julie asked.

00:09:03.940 --> 00:09:05.330
Anywhere but here, said Tabitha.

00:09:05.330 --> 00:09:05.460
I don't know.

00:09:05.460 --> 00:09:06.330
We'll get pancakes.

00:09:06.330 --> 00:09:08.260
Come on.

00:09:08.260 --> 00:09:10.010
Julie got up, the
shoulders of her T-shirt

00:09:10.010 --> 00:09:12.130
nearly even with
Tabitha's epaulets.

00:09:12.130 --> 00:09:14.520
Somehow, at 13, she had
become as tall as her sister

00:09:14.520 --> 00:09:17.005
when she wasn't
paying attention.

00:09:17.005 --> 00:09:18.760
Let me go get
dressed, she asked.

00:09:18.760 --> 00:09:20.550
You'll take forever,
said Tabitha.

00:09:20.550 --> 00:09:21.360
Come on, trust me.

00:09:21.360 --> 00:09:22.070
Let's just go.

00:09:22.070 --> 00:09:24.175
It's the millennium.

00:09:24.175 --> 00:09:26.300
Julie's flip-flops were
stacked under the coat rack

00:09:26.300 --> 00:09:26.800
by the door.

00:09:26.800 --> 00:09:28.510
She put them on and
followed Tabitha out

00:09:28.510 --> 00:09:30.120
into the front yard,
crossed the lawn

00:09:30.120 --> 00:09:32.529
in her Apple Records
T-shirt and boxers.

00:09:32.529 --> 00:09:34.070
Her legs shivered
in the spring night

00:09:34.070 --> 00:09:35.820
and every window in
every neighbor's house

00:09:35.820 --> 00:09:37.450
could have been an eyeball.

00:09:37.450 --> 00:09:39.880
She got into the car
next to her sister.

00:09:39.880 --> 00:09:41.910
She lit a cigarette, a
tulip of fire surrounded

00:09:41.910 --> 00:09:44.340
by the black petals
of her painted nails.

00:09:44.340 --> 00:09:46.860
Against the light her eyes
were red at the edges.

00:09:46.860 --> 00:09:48.970
She turned the key.

00:09:48.970 --> 00:09:51.920
They didn't talk as they
drove down 2222 and merged

00:09:51.920 --> 00:09:54.040
onto the highway bearing south.

00:09:54.040 --> 00:09:55.760
One of Tabitha's
Smashing Pumpkins CDs

00:09:55.760 --> 00:09:58.020
was blaring quietly.

00:09:58.020 --> 00:10:01.250
Tabitha tossed her filter out
the window, licked her lips,

00:10:01.250 --> 00:10:03.330
and then looked over at Julie.

00:10:03.330 --> 00:10:04.130
Shit, she said.

00:10:04.130 --> 00:10:06.130
I can't take you to get
pancakes in your boxers.

00:10:06.130 --> 00:10:08.337
I must be losing my mind.

00:10:08.337 --> 00:10:10.420
She giggled again, and she
veered off the highway,

00:10:10.420 --> 00:10:12.540
throwing Julie's shoulders
against the seatbelt.

00:10:12.540 --> 00:10:14.280
Be careful, Julie hissed.

00:10:14.280 --> 00:10:15.850
They fishtailed
under the overpass.

00:10:15.850 --> 00:10:17.120
The CD played on.

00:10:17.120 --> 00:10:19.430
Tabitha flicked her blinkers
off and on in time with it

00:10:19.430 --> 00:10:21.820
while Julie stared at her,
dug her nails into her seat.

00:10:21.820 --> 00:10:24.510
They pulled into the parking
lot of an all-night Wal-Mart.

00:10:24.510 --> 00:10:27.060
Tabitha opened the door
and swung her legs out.

00:10:27.060 --> 00:10:28.950
What are we doing
here, Julie said.

00:10:28.950 --> 00:10:30.590
What dress size are
you? said Tabitha.

00:10:30.590 --> 00:10:31.715
I have no idea, said Julie.

00:10:31.715 --> 00:10:33.064
Can we just go home?

00:10:33.064 --> 00:10:34.105
No, said Tabitha happily.

00:10:34.105 --> 00:10:34.980
Come on, guess.

00:10:34.980 --> 00:10:36.520
You have to know
your dress size.

00:10:36.520 --> 00:10:38.040
Four, Julie guessed.

00:10:38.040 --> 00:10:40.230
Four, nodded Tabitha.

00:10:40.230 --> 00:10:42.730
She took the keys out of the
ignition, tossed them to Julie,

00:10:42.730 --> 00:10:44.610
and shut the door.

00:10:44.610 --> 00:10:46.940
You can listen to the CD
if you want, she said.

00:10:46.940 --> 00:10:50.460
Just, if you do, leave the
window rolled down a little.

00:10:50.460 --> 00:10:52.710
Otherwise gases and stuff
will come in from the engine

00:10:52.710 --> 00:10:54.490
and they'll kill you.

00:10:54.490 --> 00:10:56.530
She gave a two-fingered
Cub Scout salute

00:10:56.530 --> 00:10:59.270
and then jogged off
toward the store.

00:10:59.270 --> 00:11:03.920
Julie sat alone in the car for a
minute, listening to the engine

00:11:03.920 --> 00:11:06.230
creak and settle
and needing to pee.

00:11:06.230 --> 00:11:09.390
And then she picked up the keys
and turned on the CD player.

00:11:09.390 --> 00:11:11.466
There was a new song,
quiet and creepy.

00:11:11.466 --> 00:11:13.840
A man was pushing a shopping
cart filled with bulky trash

00:11:13.840 --> 00:11:16.385
bags near the curb by the dark
part at the edge of the store,

00:11:16.385 --> 00:11:19.199
a gray hood bunched
up around his skull.

00:11:19.199 --> 00:11:20.990
She looked at the
window, half-rolled down,

00:11:20.990 --> 00:11:23.680
